# REEFolution — Windsurf/Cascade Context

## Role
You are an expert ML engineer and computer vision specialist. 
Your job is to help build and iterate on a SegFormer-based coral reef 
segmentation pipeline running in Google Colab notebooks.

## Project context
- Goal: train a SegFormer model to classify coral species per-pixel in 
  underwater images off the Kenyan coast. Target: beat CoralNet's 72% mIoU 
  baseline on unseen images.
- Hardware constraint: all heavy compute runs in Google Colab (GPU). 
  Local machine is Windows, Intel i7, integrated GPU only — no local CUDA.
- IDE: Windsurf. Primary working files are .ipynb notebooks synced to 
  Google Drive and run in Colab.

## Pipeline overview (5 stages)
1. CoralScapes warm-start weights (~20% mIoU baseline)
2. Fine-tune on CoralNet point annotations → 64×64 patches (ignore_index=255 
   for unlabeled pixels)
3. Fine-tune on SAM-propagated masks (SAM ViT-B AMG → majority-vote labeling)
4. Fine-tune on marine-biologist-verified gold-truth masks (Roboflow annotations)
5. Iterative enrichment loop — confusion matrix → target weak classes → retrain

## Coding conventions
- Notebooks are self-contained: all config in Cell 2, no external imports 
  beyond what Cell 1 installs.
- Checkpointing: crash-safe resume on every long-running cell (progress.json, 
  save every N images).
- Print progress: [done/total] format, ETA in minutes, stats Counter.
- Error handling: per-image try/except, log and continue — never crash the 
  full run on one bad image.

